[
    {
        "content": "<p>Say there are multiple occurrences of a complicated expression <code>e</code> in the context and the goal, but the exact definition of <code>e</code> doesn't matter. How could I rename <code>e</code> to an opaque variable <code>v</code> for all of its occurrences to reduce verbosity of the proof? I tried <code>let</code>, <code>rename</code>, etc., but none of these quite do what I want.<br>\nThanks!</p>",
        "id": 479964748,
        "sender_full_name": "Andrey Yao",
        "timestamp": 1730411754
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>generalize e = v</code></p>",
        "id": 479964928,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730411848
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>generalize</code> might be what you're looking for</p>",
        "id": 479964930,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1730411849
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you somehow still need to know that <code>e=v</code>, you can even use <code>generalize h:e=v</code></p>",
        "id": 479965022,
        "sender_full_name": "Edward van de Meent",
        "timestamp": 1730411890
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><code>set</code> might also work</p>",
        "id": 479965029,
